description:
In peer_try_all_pubkeys(), the function sets ctx->peer_pubkey and ctx->peer_eui64 for every peer in the table, including when verification fails:

```c
for (size_t i = 0; i < CONFIG_LICHEN_LINK_MAX_NEIGHBORS; i++) {
    if (!peer_table[i].active) {
        continue;
    }
    ctx->peer_pubkey = peer_table[i].pubkey;  // Set for this peer
    ctx->peer_eui64 = peer_table[i].eui64;
    ...
    ret = lichen_link_rx(ctx, ...);
    if (ret == 0) {
        return 0;  // Success - ctx has correct peer info
    }
    if (ret != -LICHEN_EAUTH) {
        return ret;  // ctx->peer_pubkey/eui64 point to wrong peer!
    }
}
return -LICHEN_EAUTH;  // ctx->peer_pubkey/eui64 point to last tried peer
```

When the function returns -LICHEN_EAUTH (all peers failed), the ctx contains pointers to the LAST peer tried, not any meaningful value. The caller (lichen_l2_input) doesn't use these values on failure paths, but this is a subtle contract violation.

Impact: Benign - the caller doesn't access ctx on error. P3 code quality.
